04682nam a22005415i 9780822398837DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19991999ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223988377 a10.1515/97808223988372doi  a(DE-B1597)553875  a(OCoLC)1229160898  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aBD639b.L85 1998 7aPHI0130002bisacsh04a1152211 aLukacher, Ned, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTime-Fetishes :bThe Secret History of Eternal Recurrence /cNed Lukacher. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (192 p.) :b5 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tI The Ancients -- t1. The Anachrony of the Time-Fetish -- t2. From Ovid to Titian: Eternal Return and the Cult of Bacchus and Ariadne -- tII Shakespeare -- t3. "Shakespearances"; or, The War with Time -- t4. Anamorphic Perspectives, Human (Im)postures, and the Rhetoric of the Aevum -- tIII The Moderns -- t5. Anamorphic Ghosts of Time: Schopenhauer, Kant, and Hegel -- t6. Drive-Time: Eternal Return and the Life of the Instincts in Schelling, Freud, and the Marquis de Sade -- t7. Playing with Cinders: From Nietzsche to Derrida -- t8. Forgetting the Umbrella; or, Heidegger and Derrida on How to Say the Same Thing Differently -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor over two and a half millennia human beings have attempted to invent strategies to "discover" the truth of time, to determine whether time is infinite, whether eternity is the infinite duration of a continuous present, or whether it too rises and falls with the cycles of universal creation and destruction. Time-Fetishes recounts the history of a tradition that runs counter to the dominant tradition in Western metaphysics, which has sought to purify eternity of its temporal character. From the pre-Socratics to Ovid and Plotinus, and from Shakespeare to Hegel, Schelling, Nietzsche, Heidegger, and Derrida, Time-Fetishes traces the secret tradition of the idea of eternal recurrence and situates it as the grounding thought of Western philosophy and literature.The thinkers in this counter-history of the eternal return lingered long enough on the question of time to learn how to resist separating eternity from time, and how to reflect on the possible identity of time and eternity as a way of resisting all prior metaphysical determinations. Drawing out the implications of Nietzsche's reinvention of the doctrine of return, Lukacher ranges across a broad spectrum of ancient and modern thinkers. Shakespeare's role in this history as the "poet of time" is particularly significant, for not only does Shakespeare reactivate the pre-Christian arguments of eternal return, he regards them, and all arguments and images concerning the essence of time and Being, from an inimitably ironic perspective.As he makes transitions from literature to philosophy and psychoanalysis, Lukacher displays a theoretical imagination and historical vision that bring to the forefront a host of pre- and post-Christian texts in order to decipher in them an encounter with the thought of eternal recurrence that has been too long buried under layers of rigid metaphysical interpretation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aEternal returnxHistory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Metaphysics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822398837zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822398837423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780